recordings.rmk: next to the nest hole
A bird had calling in trees beside a footpath. I saw Eurasian Nuthatch close by and suspect this is another one of its calls

The song of the Eurasian Nuthatch (EN) consists of a series of similar syllables as judged by many recordings on this site. 

The bird of the present recordings changes the character of syllables and tempo of the song several times within a very short period of time, twelve seconds. Yet, there is the impression that this may be the song of a EN. The bird did not produce any other recordable sounds. Does anyone agree with EN or is this a different species?
Whiiy-calls

I heard the bird in the early afternoon, on a bright sunny dag. 
The bird was sitting at the top of the tree. 
It was to high for me to see it clearly, but it looked half white at the chest, half brown on the tail side. 
The bird made its call (ti ti ti ti ti)  stopped for a few seconds, turned and then made its call again after 10 seconds, this time a little bit longer (but it is possible that my recording started a little bit late).
The size is like a wood pigeon, I guess. 
I filmed it with my Iphone. The sound is directly recorded and there are no other sounds on the recording than soft traffic and wind noises. You can hear the bird clearly.
I have never heard or seen this bird in my surroundings and friends also didn't recognised it. 
I posted it on my Facebook and a friend said she had heard it at her back yard a day earlyer. 
She also hadn't heard it before. I can't find it on my birdapp Tuinvogels from the Vogelbescherming Nederland.
So, who can help me?

recordings.rmk:
This extract is as recorded with no edit except select fragment from longer piece and remove some sections where target bird was not singing. Bird seemed to be singing from a tree top (not seen, only sound located). The call was repeated a number of times . The weather was quiet, high cloud, cool with sunny spells. I would be very interested to know what bird it is and what the purpose of its song is in this recording. Thank you Xeno Canto community.

UPDATE Many thanks to Ireneusz Oleksik for identifying this as a Eurasian Nuthatch. 

Looking through the Greek website of rare birds in Greece...the Siita Europaea  is listed.
